ity relationships, finishing education and getting started in a career) began doing chores at three to four years of age, whereas those who waited until their teen years to start doing chores were comparatively less successful.","note":"Jennifer Breheny Wallace\r\n*The Wall Street Journal*, 2015","link_url":"http://www.wsj.com/articles/why-children-need-chores-1426262655","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Raising Can-Do Kids: Giving Children the Tools to Thrive in a Fast-Changing World*","blurb":"Professor Richard Rende of Brown University writes about the academic and social benefits of doing chores.","note":"Richard Rende\r\nTarcherPerigee, 2016","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Raising-Can-Do-Kids-Children-Fast-Changing/dp/0399168974/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*The Childhood Roots of Adult Happiness: Five Steps to Help Kids Create and Sustain Lifetime Joy*","blurb":"Professor Edward “Ned” Hallowell at Harvard University also describes the value of chores or ‘industriousness in childhood’ as predictors of success in the workplace and well-being.","note":"Edward M. Hallowell\r\nBallantine Books, 2002","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Childhood-Roots-Adult-Happiness-Lifelong/dp/0345442334/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null}]},{"title":"Help Stressed-Out Kids Turn Things Around","description":"","rec_items":[{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Overloaded and Underprepared: Strategies for Stronger Schools and Healthy, Successful Kids*","blurb":"This book helps parents and educators reduce student stress while engaging kids in real learning, written by the leaders of the non-profit Challenge Success.","note":"Denise Pope, Maureen Brown and Sarah Miles\r\nJossey-